Passive VISIR spectroscopy, also known as VIS-NIR-SWIR reflectance spectroscopy, is widely used for the detection and identification of both organic and inorganic compounds. It relies on the targets being illuminated by artificial light sources in the laboratory or by the Sun for field work and planetary exploration. It exploits the fact that molecules absorb frequencies that are characteristic of their structure. Such absorption occurs at resonant frequencies when the frequency of the absorbed radiation matches the molecular vibrational frequencies (Fig. 5). Typical vibrational frequencies range from ∼1013\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
