In the end, we have noted that the microphone is sensitive to electromagnetic noise from the rest of the experiment, but fortunately not from the rover equipment as could be checked during ATLO tests at JPL. The perturbations come from the laser stack heater at ∼76Hz\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sim76~\text{Hz}$\end{document} and its harmonics (the non-laser, standalone microphone mode is not affected since the laser thermal control is inactive). Since the laser-induced signal is repeated several times (as many times as the number of laser shots), an average waveform can be built from the stacking of the various signals, which have been filtered in the time and frequency domains. The correlation of each pulse with the average signature allows us to retrieve a signal cleaned from the perturbation after several iterations.

Each MIC data product is required to be ≤8MB\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\leq8~\text{MB}$\end{document}, the volume of an uncompressed RMI image. The microphone has three recording modes: i) the standalone mode for natural and artificial sounds, up to 2.46 min at 25 kHz, ii) the LIBS continuous mode around a burst of laser shots, up to 120 shots, which at 3 Hz is equivalent to 40 s of recording, and iii) the LIBS pulsed mode. In the latter mode, the microphone is synchronized with the pulsed laser frequency. For each laser shot, the recording starts 500 μs before the laser fires and lasts for 60 ms. The shock-wave direct signal is expected to arrive between 5.5 ms (for a target at 1.5 m at 10∘C\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
