				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$>110~\text{A}$\end{document}”. This “laser exclusion zone” issue is known from ChemCam, which has two separate exclusion zones, including one on the surface of Mars, at around ∼2m\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\sim2~\text{m}$\end{document}. SuperCam was designed to eliminate the latter one. Regrettably, SuperCam’s calibration targets are at a distance from 1.54 to 1.57 m, tangent to the exclusion zone. Thus, the number of LIBS laser shots on the calibration targets will be recorded as a consumable during operations.

