SuperCam has several operating modes, each one having its own power requirement and duration. Consequently, the instrument energy requirement depends on the sequence of modes used. Hence a notional 25 min sequence is proposed: Body Unit on, TEC cooling from 30∘C\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$30~^{\circ }\text{C}$\end{document} RAMP, Mast Unit on (when CCDs approach their operating temperature), lasers warm up, CWL AF, RMI, 30 LIBS spectra at 3 Hz with microphone, 10 collects of 10 Raman spectra, a VISIR spectrum (128 spectels for IRS), RMI image, transfer of data to RCE, and turn both units off. This sequence does not necessarily represent a sequence of operations that would actually be executed on Mars. Instead, its role is to provide some idea of how SuperCam’s resources have evolved from early development to final delivery. Based on the notional sequence, the Mast Unit will use 18 W.hr.

A comprehensive set of Verification Activities (VAs) was defined to validate the functionalities and high-level technical requirements of the Mast Unit. All VAs were first run at room temperature before mechanical and thermal tests. A subset was run after these tests to validate the robustness of the instrument design. Most of them were performed on the different dwells during the two-week long thermal vacuum tests (TVAC). The Mast Unit was operating under 7 mbar of N2 over the AFT range. Validation activities cover: 
Telescope focus: 
Positions of close and infinite focus, end switches hysteresis, distance vs. steps laws;
CWL AF and RMI AF, validation of algorithm, duration, repeatability;
Offset laws between CWL AF, RMI AF, and best position for LIBS;
CW laser power.
Red and green laser beams: 
Energy vs. pumping current, long and short bursts;
Red laser beam irradiance and green laser beam footprint;
Long and short bursts, margins to relaxation mode;
Alignment of red and green laser beams, CWL, all with fiber, RMI, and IRS;
Timing of laser beams relative to the Body-Unit spectrometers.
Light collect: 
Relative optical transmission to fiber, RMI, and IRS;
Fiber FOV and DoF;
IR FOV and DoF.
Remote Micro-Imaging: 
Dark current, offset level;
FOV, DOF, and flat field characterization;
Spatial resolution (absolute around the center, and relative on the edges);
Auto-exposure and HDR algorithms.
Microphone: 
Gains, background noise;
Electromagnetic noise with LIBS;
Synchronization with LIBS.
Infrared Spectrometer: 
TEC cool down;
Dark current, RF profile. The TVAC results validate (and calibrate) all Mast-Unit L5 requirements that are defined in Sect. 3.3, for different temperatures between −40∘C\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
